The triangular defect in the lower anterior abdominal wall, open bladder plate with an exposed urethra, and a low set umbilicus suggests bladder exstrophy. The anteriorly displaced anus suggests imperforate anus, and the shortened penis with a pronounced upward curvature and the urethral opening along the dorsal surface suggests epispadias.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presence of an open bladder plate with an exposed urethra, an anteriorly displaced anus, a low set umbilicus, and an inguinal hernia suggest bladder exstrophy. The external genitalia abnormalities, such as a shortened penis with an upward curve and dorsal urethral opening, are also consistent with bladder exstrophy. Cloacal exstrophy may present with similar findings, but it typically involves a more extensive defect involving the bladder, rectum, and external genitalia. Urachal cyst and posterior urethral valves are not associated with the described physical findings.
